children.name: Set
contains
children.comment: Returns true if [value] is in the set.

children.name: add
children.comment:
Adds [value] into the set. The method has no effect if
[value] was already in the set.

children.name: remove
children.comment:
Removes [value] from the set. Returns true if [value] was
in the set. Returns false otherwise. The method has no effect
if [value] value was not in the set.

children.name: isSubsetOf
children.comment:
Returns true if [collection] contains all the elements of this
collection.

children.name: containsAll
children.comment:
Returns true if this collection contains all the elements of
[collection].

children.name: intersection
children.comment:
Returns a new set which is the intersection between this set and
the given collection.

children.name: clear
children.comment: Removes all elements in the set.

children.name: Set.from
children.comment: Creates a [Set] that contains all elements of [other].

This class is the public interface of a set. A set is a collection
without duplicates.

children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.

children.name: toString
children.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

children.name: noSuchMethod
children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [InvocationMirror].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].

children.name: hashCode
children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

children.name: runtimeType
children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

children.name: Object
children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.
Everything in Dart is an [Object].

children.name: Map
containsValue
children.comment: Returns whether this map contains the given [value].

children.name: containsKey
children.comment: Returns whether this map contains the given [key].

Returns the value for the given [key] or null if [key] is not
in the map. Because null values are supported, one should either
use containsKey to distinguish between an absent key and a null
value, or use the [putIfAbsent] method.
Associates the [key] with the given [value].

children.name: putIfAbsent
children.comment:
If [key] is not associated to a value, calls [ifAbsent] and
updates the map by mapping [key] to the value returned by
[ifAbsent]. Returns the value in the map.

It is an error to add or remove keys from map during the call to
[ifAbsent].

children.name: remove
children.comment:
Removes the association for the given [key]. Returns the value for
[key] in the map or null if [key] is not in the map. Note that values
can be null and a returned null value does not always imply that the
key is absent.

children.name: clear
children.comment: Removes all pairs from the map.

children.name: forEach
children.comment:
Applies [f] to each {key, value} pair of the map.

It is an error to add or remove keys from the map during iteration.

children.name: keys
children.comment: The keys of [this].

children.name: values
children.comment: The values of [this].

children.name: length
children.comment: The number of {key, value} pairs in the map.

children.name: isEmpty
children.comment: Returns true if there is no {key, value} pair in the map.

children.name: Map
children.comment: Creates a map with the default implementation.

children.name: Map.from
children.comment: Creates a [Map] that contains all key value pairs of [other].

A [Map] is an associative container, mapping a key to a value.
Null values are supported, but null keys are not.

children.name: List

children.comment:
Returns the element at the given [index] in the list or throws
an [RangeError] if [index] is out of bounds.

Sets the entry at the given [index] in the list to [value].
Throws an [RangeError] if [index] is out of bounds.

children.name: length=
children.comment:
Changes the length of the list. If [newLength] is greater than
the current [length], entries are initialized to [:null:]. Throws
an [UnsupportedError] if the list is not extendable.

children.name: add
children.comment:
Adds [value] at the end of the list, extending the length by
one. Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the list is not
extendable.

children.name: addLast
children.comment:
Adds [value] at the end of the list, extending the length by
one. Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the list is not
extendable.

children.name: addAll
children.comment:
Appends all elements of the [iterable] to the end of this list.
Extends the length of the list by the number of elements in [iterable].
Throws an [UnsupportedError] if this list is not extensible.

children.name: sort
children.comment:
Sorts the list according to the order specified by the [compare] function.

The [compare] function must act as a [Comparator].
The default [List] implementations use [Comparable.compare] if
[compare] is omitted.

children.name: indexOf
children.comment:
Returns the first index of [element] in the list.

Searches the list from index [start] to the length of the list.
The first time an element [:e:] is encountered so that [:e == element:],
the index of [:e:] is returned.
Returns -1 if [element] is not found.

children.name: lastIndexOf
children.comment:
Returns the last index of [element] in the list.

Searches the list backwards from index [start] (inclusive) to 0.
The first time an element [:e:] is encountered so that [:e == element:],
the index of [:e:] is returned.
If start is not provided, it defaults to [:this.length - 1:] .
Returns -1 if [element] is not found.

children.name: clear
children.comment:
Removes all elements in the list.

The length of the list becomes zero.
Throws an [UnsupportedError], and retains all elements, if the
length of the list cannot be changed.

children.name: removeAt
children.comment:
Removes the element at position[index] from the list.

This reduces the length of the list by one and moves all later elements
down by one position.
Returns the removed element.
Throws an [ArgumentError] if [index] is not an [int].
Throws an [RangeError] if the [index] does not point inside
the list.
Throws an [UnsupportedError], and doesn't remove the element,
if the length of the list cannot be changed.

children.name: removeLast
children.comment:
Pops and returns the last element of the list.
Throws a [UnsupportedError] if the length of the
list cannot be changed.

children.name: getRange
children.comment:
Returns a new list containing [length] elements from the list,
starting at  [start].
Returns an empty list if [length] is 0.
Throws an [ArgumentError] if [length] is negative.
Throws an [RangeError] if [start] or
[:start + length - 1:] are out of range.

children.name: setRange
children.comment:
Copies [length] elements of [from], starting
at [startFrom], into the list, starting at [start].
If [length] is 0, this method does not do anything.
Throws an [ArgumentError] if [length] is negative.
Throws an [RangeError] if [start] or
[:start + length - 1:] are out of range for [:this:], or if
[startFrom] or [:startFrom + length - 1:] are out of range for [from].

children.name: removeRange
children.comment:
Removes [length] elements from the list, beginning at [start].
Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the list is
not extendable.
If [length] is 0, this method does not do anything.
Throws an [ArgumentError] if [length] is negative.
Throws an [RangeError] if [start] or
[:start + length: - 1] are out of range.

children.name: insertRange
children.comment:
Inserts a new range into the list, starting from [start] to
[:start + length - 1:]. The entries are filled with [fill].
Throws an [UnsupportedError] if the list is
not extendable.
If [length] is 0, this method does not do anything.
If [start] is the length of the list, this method inserts the
range at the end of the list.
Throws an [ArgumentError] if [length] is negative.
Throws an [RangeError] if [start] is negative or if
[start] is greater than the length of the list.

children.name: reversed
children.comment: Returns an [Iterable] of the elements of this [List] in reverse order.

children.name: List
children.comment:
Creates a list of the given [length].

The length of the returned list is not fixed.

children.name: List.fixedLength
children.comment:
Creates a fixed-sized list of the given [length] where each entry is
filled with [fill].

children.name: List.from
children.comment:
Creates an list with the elements of [other]. The order in
the list will be the order provided by the iterator of [other].

The length of the returned list is not fixed.

A [List] is an indexable collection with a length. It can be of
fixed size or extendable.

children.name: Iterator
moveNext
children.comment:
Moves to the next element. Returns true if [current] contains the next
element. Returns false, if no element was left.

It is safe to invoke [moveNext] even when the iterator is already
positioned after the last element. In this case [moveNext] has no effect.

children.name: current
children.comment:
Returns the current element.

Return [:null:] if the iterator has not yet been moved to the first
element, or if the iterator has been moved after the last element of the
[Iterable].

The [Iterator] class provides methods to iterate over an object. It
is transparently used by the for-in construct to test for the end
of the iteration, and to get the elements.

If the object iterated over is changed during the iteration, the
behavior is unspecified.

The [Iterator] is initially positioned before the first element. Before
accessing the first element the iterator must thus be advanced ([moveNext])
to point to the first element. If there is no element left, then [moveNext]
returns false.

A typical usage of an [Iterator] looks as follows:

    var it = obj.iterator;
    while (it.moveNext()) {
      use(it.current);
    }

children.name: Iterable
map
children.comment:
Returns a lazy [Iterable] where each element [:e:] of [this] is replaced
by the result of [:f(e):].

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the
returned [Iterable] is not iterated over, the supplied function [f] will
not be invoked. The transformed elements will not be cached. Iterating
multiple times over the the returned [Iterable] will invoke the supplied
function [f] multiple times on the same element.

children.name: where
children.comment:
Returns a lazy [Iterable] with all elements that satisfy the
predicate [f].

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the
returned [Iterable] is not iterated over, the supplied function [f] will
not be invoked. Iterating will not cache results, and thus iterating
multiple times over the the returned [Iterable] will invoke the supplied
function [f] multiple times on the same element.

children.name: expand
children.comment:
Expand each element of this [Iterable] into zero or more elements.

The resulting Iterable will run through the elements returned
by [f] for each element of this, in order.

The returned [Iterable] is lazy, and will call [f] for each element
of this every time it's iterated.

children.name: contains
children.comment: Check whether the collection contains an element equal to [element].

children.name: forEach
children.comment: Applies the function [f] to each element of this collection.

children.name: reduce
children.comment:
Reduce a collection to a single value by iteratively combining each element
of the collection with an existing value using the provided function.
Use [initialValue] as the initial value, and the function [combine] to
create a new value from the previous one and an element.

Example of calculating the sum of a collection:

  collection.reduce(0, (prev, element) => prev + element);

children.name: every
children.comment:
Returns true if every elements of this collection satisify the
predicate [f]. Returns false otherwise.

children.name: join
children.comment:
Convert each element to a [String] and concatenate the strings.

Converts each element to a [String] by calling [Object.toString] on it.
Then concatenates the strings, optionally separated by the [separator]
string.

children.name: any
children.comment:
Returns true if one element of this collection satisfies the
predicate [f]. Returns false otherwise.

children.name: min
children.comment:
Find the least element in the iterable.

Returns null if the iterable is empty.
Otherwise returns an element [:x:] of this [Iterable] so that
[:x:] is not greater than [:y:] (that is, [:compare(x, y) <= 0:]) for all
other elements [:y:] in the iterable.

The [compare] function must be a proper [Comparator<T>]. If a function is
not provided, [compare] defaults to [Comparable.compare].

children.name: max
children.comment:
Find the largest element in the iterable.

Returns null if the iterable is empty.
Otherwise returns an element [:x:] of this [Iterable] so that
[:x:] is not smaller than [:y:] (that is, [:compare(x, y) >= 0:]) for all
other elements [:y:] in the iterable.

The [compare] function must be a proper [Comparator<T>]. If a function is
not provided, [compare] defaults to [Comparable.compare].

children.name: take
children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] with at most [n] elements.

The returned [Iterable] may contain fewer than [n] elements, if [this]
contains fewer than [n] elements.

children.name: takeWhile
children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that stops once [test] is not satisfied anymore.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new [Iterator] of the returned
[Iterable] will start iterating over the elements of [this].
When the iterator encounters an element [:e:] that does not satisfy [test],
it discards [:e:] and moves into the finished state. That is, it will not
ask or provide any more elements.

children.name: skip
children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that skips the first [n] elements.

If [this] has fewer than [n] elements, then the resulting [Iterable] will
be empty.

children.name: skipWhile
children.comment:
Returns an [Iterable] that skips elements while [test] is satisfied.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new [Iterator] of the returned
[Iterable] will iterate over all elements of [this].
As long as the iterator's elements do not satisfy [test] they are
discarded. Once an element satisfies the [test] the iterator stops testing
and uses every element unconditionally.

children.name: firstMatching
children.comment:
Returns the first element that satisfies the given predicate [f].

If none matches, the result of invoking the [orElse] function is
returned. By default, when [orElse] is `null`, a [StateError] is
thrown.

children.name: lastMatching
children.comment:
Returns the last element that satisfies the given predicate [f].

If none matches, the result of invoking the [orElse] function is
returned. By default, when [orElse] is [:null:], a [StateError] is
thrown.

children.name: singleMatching
children.comment:
Returns the single element that satisfies [f]. If no or more than one
element match then a [StateError] is thrown.

children.name: elementAt
children.comment:
Returns the [index]th element.

If [this] [Iterable] has fewer than [index] elements throws a
[RangeError].

Note: if [this] does not have a deterministic iteration order then the
function may simply return any element without any iteration if there are
at least [index] elements in [this].

children.name: iterator
children.comment: Returns an [Iterator] that iterates over this [Iterable] object.

children.name: length
children.comment:
Returns the number of elements in [this].

Counting all elements may be involve running through all elements and can
therefore be slow.

children.name: isEmpty
children.comment: Returns true if there is no element in this collection.

children.name: first
children.comment:
Returns the first element.

If [this] is empty throws a [StateError]. Otherwise this method is
equivalent to [:this.elementAt(0):]

children.name: last
children.comment:
Returns the last element.

If [this] is empty throws a [StateError].

children.name: single
children.comment:
Returns the single element in [this].

If [this] is empty or has more than one element throws a [StateError].

children.name: Iterable.generate
children.comment:
Create an [Iterable] that generates its elements dynamically.

The [Iterators] created by the [Iterable] will count from
zero to [:count - 1:] while iterating, and call [generator]
with that index to create the next value.

As an [Iterable], [:new Iterable.generate(n, generator)):] is equivalent to
[:const [0, ..., n - 1].map(generator):]

The [Iterable] interface allows to get an [Iterator] out of an
[Iterable] object.

This interface is used by the for-in construct to iterate over an
[Iterable] object.
The for-in construct takes an [Iterable] object at the right-hand
side, and calls its [iterator] method to get an [Iterator] on it.

A user-defined class that implements the [Iterable] interface can
be used as the right-hand side of a for-in construct.

children.name: Collection
add
children.comment: Adds an element to this collection.

children.name: addAll
children.comment:
Adds all of [elements] to this collection.

Equivalent to adding each element in [elements] using [add],
but some collections may be able to optimize it.

children.name: remove
children.comment:
Removes an instance of [element] from this collection.

This removes only one instance of the element for collections that can
contain the same element more than once (e.g., [List]). Which instance
is removed is decided by the collection.

Has no effect if the elements is not in this collection.

children.name: removeAll
children.comment:
Removes all of [elements] from this collection.

Equivalent to calling [remove] once for each element in
[elements], but may be faster for some collections.

children.name: retainAll
children.comment:
Removes all elements of this collection that are not
in [elements].

For [Set]s, this is the intersection of the two original sets.

children.name: removeMatching
children.comment:
Removes all elements of this collection that satisfy [test].

An elements [:e:] satisfies [test] if [:test(e):] is true.

children.name: retainMatching
children.comment:
Removes all elements of this collection that fail to satisfy [test].

An elements [:e:] satisfies [test] if [:test(e):] is true.

children.name: clear
children.comment: Removes all elements of this collection.

A collection of individual elements.

A [Collection] contains some elements in a structure optimized
for certain operations. Different collections are optimized for different
uses.

A collection can be updated by adding or removing elements.

Collections are [Iterable]. The order of iteration is defined by
each type of collection.

children.name: UnmodifiableListBase
children.comment: An unmodifiable [List].

children.name: ListBase
children.comment:
Class implementing the read-operations on [List].

Implements all read-only operations, except [:operator[]:] and [:length:],
in terms of those two operations.

children.name: LinkedHashMap
children.comment: A hash-based map that iterates keys and values in key insertion order.

children.name: _addAllEntries
children.comment: Copies all non-free entries from the old table to the new empty table.

children.name: _LinkedHashTableHeadMarker
children.comment: Unique marker object for the head of a linked list of entries.

children.name: _HashTableIterable
_valueAt
children.comment: Return the iterated value for a given entry.
Generic iterable based on a [_HashTable].

children.name: _key
children.comment: Reads key from table. Converts _NULL marker to null.

children.name: _setKey
children.comment: Writes key to table. Converts null to _NULL marker.

children.name: _createTable
children.comment: Create an empty table.

children.name: _firstProbe
children.comment: First table probe.

children.name: _nextProbe
children.comment: Following table probes.

children.name: _isFree
children.comment: Whether an object is a free-marker (either tombstone or free).

children.name: _probeForAdd
children.comment:
Look up the offset for an object in the table.

Finds the offset of the object in the table, if it is there,
or the first free offset for its hashCode.

children.name: _probeForLookup
children.comment:
Look up the offset for an object in the table.

If the object is in the table, its offset is returned.

If the object is not in the table, Otherwise a negative value is returned.

children.name: _equals
children.comment:
Compare two object for equality.

The first object is the one already in the table,
and the second is the one being searched for.

children.name: _hashCodeOf
children.comment: Compute hash-code for an object.

children.name: _checkCapacity
children.comment:
Ensure that the table isn't too full for its own good.

Call this after adding an element.

children.name: _addAllEntries
children.comment: Copies all non-free entries from the old table to the new empty table.

children.name: _copyEntry
children.comment:
Copies everything but the key element from one entry to another.

Called while growing the base array.

Override this if any non-key fields need copying.

children.name: _get
children.comment: Returns the offset of a key in [_table], or negative if it's not there.

children.name: _put
children.comment:
Puts the key into the table and returns its offset into [_table].

If [_entrySize] is greater than 1, the caller should fill the
remaining fields.

Remember to call [_checkCapacity] after using this method.

children.name: _remove
children.comment:
Removes a key from the table and returns its offset into [_table].

Returns null if the key was not in the table.
If [_entrySize] is greater than 1, the caller should clean up the
remaining fields.

children.name: _clear
children.comment: Clears the table completely, leaving it empty.

children.name: _deleteEntry
children.comment: Clears an entry in the table.

children.name: _entrySize
children.comment: Size of each entry.

children.name: _rebuildWorkList
children.comment:
Called when the tree structure of the map has changed.

This can be caused by a splay operation.
If the key-set changes, iteration is aborted before getting
here, so we know that the keys are the same as before, it's
only the tree that has been reordered.

children.name: SplayTreeMap
_splay
children.comment:
Perform the splay operation for the given key. Moves the node with
the given key to the top of the tree.  If no node has the given
key, the last node on the search path is moved to the top of the
tree. This is the simplified top-down splaying algorithm from:
"Self-adjusting Binary Search Trees" by Sleator and Tarjan.

Returns the result of comparing the new root of the tree to [key].
Returns -1 if the table is empty.

children.name: _addNewRoot
children.comment:
Adds a new root node with the given [key] or [value].

The [comp] value is the result of comparing the existing root's key
with key.

children.name: firstKey
children.comment: Get the first key in the map. Returns [null] if the map is empty.

children.name: lastKey
children.comment: Get the last key in the map. Returns [null] if the map is empty.

children.name: lastKeyBefore
children.comment:
Get the last key in the map that is strictly smaller than [key]. Returns
[null] if no key was not found.

children.name: firstKeyAfter
children.comment:
Get the first key in the map that is strictly larger than [key]. Returns
[null] if no key was not found.

A splay tree is a self-balancing binary
search tree with the additional property that recently accessed
elements are quick to access again. It performs basic operations
such as insertion, look-up and removal in O(log(n)) amortized time.

This implementation is a Dart version of the JavaScript
implementation in the V8 project.

children.name: SplayTreeNode
children.comment:
A node in a splay tree. It holds the key, the value and the left
and right children in the tree.

children.name: _ListQueueIterator
children.comment:
Iterator for a [ListQueue].

Considers any add or remove operation a concurrent modification.

children.name: ListQueue
removeMatching
children.comment:
Remove all elements matched by [test].

This method is inefficient since it works by repeatedly removing single
elements, each of which can take linear time.

children.name: retainMatching
children.comment:
Remove all elements not matched by [test].

This method is inefficient since it works by repeatedly removing single
elements, each of which can take linear time.

children.name: _isPowerOf2
children.comment:
Whether [number] is a power of two.

Only works for positive numbers.

children.name: _nextPowerOf2
children.comment:
Rounds [number] up to the nearest power of 2.

If [number] is a power of 2 already, it is returned.

Only works for positive numbers.

children.name: _checkModification
children.comment: Check if the queue has been modified during iteration.

children.name: _add
children.comment: Adds element at end of queue. Used by both [add] and [addAll].

children.name: _remove
children.comment:
Removes the element at [offset] into [_table].

Removal is performed by linerarly moving elements either before or after
[offset] by one position.

Returns the new offset of the following element. This may be the same
offset or the following offset depending on how elements are moved
to fill the hole.

children.name: _grow
children.comment: Grow the table when full.

children.name: _preGrow
children.comment: Grows the table even if it is not full.

children.name: ListQueue
children.comment:
Create an empty queue.

If [initialCapacity] is given, prepare the queue for at least that many
elements.

children.name: ListQueue.from
children.comment: Create a queue initially containing the elements of [source].

List based [Queue].

Keeps a cyclic buffer of elements, and grows to a larger buffer when
it fills up. This guarantees constant time peek and remove operations, and
amortized constant time add operations.

The structure is efficient for any queue or stack usage.

Collection operations like [removeAll] and [removeMatching] are very
inefficient. If those are needed, use a [DoubleLinkedQueue] instead.

children.name: DoubleLinkedQueue
children.comment:
A [Queue] implementation based on a double-linked list.

Allows constant time add, remove-at-ends and peek operations.

Can do [removeAll] and [retainAll] in linear time.

children.name: _DoubleLinkedQueueEntrySentinel
children.comment:
A sentinel in a double linked list is used to manipulate the list
at both ends. A double linked list has exactly one sentinel, which
is the only entry when the list is constructed. Initially, a
sentinel has its next and previous entry point to itself. A
sentinel does not box any user element.

children.name: DoubleLinkedQueueEntry
children.comment:
An entry in a doubly linked list. It contains a pointer to the next
entry, the previous entry, and the boxed element.

WARNING: This class is temporary located in dart:core. It'll be removed
at some point in the near future.

children.name: Queue
removeFirst
children.comment:
Removes and returns the first element of this queue. Throws an
[StateError] exception if this queue is empty.

children.name: removeLast
children.comment:
Removes and returns the last element of the queue. Throws an
[StateError] exception if this queue is empty.

children.name: addFirst
children.comment: Adds [value] at the beginning of the queue.

children.name: addLast
children.comment: Adds [value] at the end of the queue.

children.name: add
children.comment: Adds [value] at the end of the queue.

children.name: addAll
children.comment:
Adds all elements of [iterable] at the end of the queue. The
length of the queue is extended by the length of [iterable].

children.name: clear
children.comment: Removes all elements in the queue. The size of the queue becomes zero.

children.name: Queue
children.comment: Creates a queue.

children.name: Queue.from
children.comment:
Creates a queue with the elements of [other]. The order in
the queue will be the order provided by the iterator of [other].

A [Queue] is a collection that can be manipulated at both ends. One
can iterate over the elements of a queue through [forEach] or with
an [Iterator].

children.name: mapToString
children.comment:
Returns a string representing the specified map. The returned string
looks like this: [:'{key0: value0, key1: value1, ... keyN: valueN}':].
The value returned by its [toString] method is used to represent each
key or value.

If the map collection contains a reference to itself, either
directly as a key or value, or indirectly through other collections
or maps, the contained reference is rendered as [:'{...}':]. This
prevents the infinite regress that would otherwise occur. So, for example,
calling this method on a map whose sole entry maps the string key 'me'
to a reference to the map would return [:'{me: {...}}':].

A typical implementation of a map's [toString] method will
simply return the results of this method applied to the collection.

children.name: HasNextIterator
children.comment:
The [HasNextIterator] class wraps an [Iterator] and provides methods to
iterate over an object using `hasNext` and `next`.

An [HasNextIterator] does not implement the [Iterator] interface.

children.name: UnmodifiableListView
UnmodifiableListView
children.comment: Create an unmodifiable list backed by [source].

An unmodifiable [List] view of another List.

The source of the elements may be a [List] or any [Iterable] with
efficient [Iterable.length] and [Iterable.elementAt].

children.name: IterableMixinWorkaround
removeAll
children.comment:
Simple implementation for [Collection.removeAll].

This implementation assumes that [Collection.remove] on [collection]
is efficient. The [:remove:] method on [List] objects is typically
not efficient since it requires linear search to find an element.

children.name: removeAllList
children.comment:
Implementation of [Collection.removeAll] for lists.

This implementation assumes that [Collection.remove] is not efficient
(as it usually isn't on a [List]) and uses [Collection.removeMathcing]
instead of just repeatedly calling remove.

children.name: retainAll
children.comment:
Simple implemenation for [Collection.retainAll].

This implementation assumes that [Collecton.retainMatching] on [collection]
is efficient.

children.name: removeMatching
children.comment:
Simple implemenation for [Collection.removeMatching].

This implementation assumes that [Collecton.removeAll] on [collection] is
efficient.

children.name: removeMatchingList
children.comment:
Removes elements matching [test] from [list].

This is performed in two steps, to avoid exposing an inconsistent state
to the [test] function. First the elements to ratain are found, and then
the original list is updated to contain those elements.

children.name: retainMatching
children.comment:
Simple implemenation for [Collection.retainMatching].

This implementation assumes that [Collecton.removeAll] on [collection] is
efficient.

This class provides default implementations for Iterables (including Lists).

Once Dart receives Mixins it will be replaced with mixin classes.

children.name: indexOf
children.comment:
Returns the index in the list [a] of the given [element], starting
the search at index [startIndex] to [endIndex] (exclusive).
Returns -1 if [element] is not found.

children.name: lastIndexOf
children.comment:
Returns the last index in the list [a] of the given [element], starting
the search at index [startIndex] to 0.
Returns -1 if [element] is not found.
